With the economy tanking and families locked together because of stay-at-home orders to combat the spread of the coronavirus pandemic, domestic violence rates appear to be soaring.
Finland’s liquor store employee strike in the 1970s as well as Sweden’s curtailment of liquor store sales on certain days in the 1980s, both had that effect.
Not only did drunk driving rates fall, but so did calls for domestic violence — both by about 10 percent.
Calls to domestic violence support lines require privacy as well, although text chat is an increasingly available silent alternative.
With liquor stores closed, many people addicted to alcohol will have to endure the physical effects of withdrawal.